n		        This week is one of the busiest leading to WordCamp Europe. As of today, we have sold 2100 tickets and this week we&#8217;ll release the rest of the reserved tickets to bring us to the magical number of 3000 attendees. &#8230; Continue reading A busy week ahead of us – today we&#8217;re releasing reserved tickets; schedule to be published on Friday  &#8594;		        ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:15:"WordCamp Europe";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3238:"<div id="attachment_5190" style="width: 1410px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img class="wp-image-5190 size-full" src="http://2017.europe.wordcamp.org/files/2017/05/reserved-tickets-1.jpg" alt="" width="1400" height="800" /><p class="wp-caption-text">We are releasing all reserved (but unclaimed) tickets today; and plan to publish final schedule on Friday</p></div>\n<p>This week is one of the busiest leading to WordCamp Europe. As of today, <strong>we have sold 2100 tickets</strong> and this week we&#8217;ll release the<strong> rest of the reserved tickets to bring us to the magical number of 3000 attendees</strong>. But not only that – you often asked us &#8220;when will you publish the schedule?&#8221; Well, your wait is (almost) over. We&#8217;re happy to say that the <strong>final schedule will be announced this week</strong> – as soon as we finish rolling out speaker announcements.</p>\n<p><span id="more-5157"></span></p>\n<h2>Releasing 670 reserved tickets</h2>\n<p>We released the first batch of tickets after the closing remarks in Vienna and the final batch in February. As of today <strong>we have sold 2100 tickets</strong>, which is absolutely fantastic! With that, a month and a half before the event, we have <strong>surpassed the number of attendees we had in Vienna</strong>.</p>\n<p>As WordCamp Europe grows, we aim not only for more attendees but for more speakers, volunteers and sponsors as well. To make sure everyone will be able to attend before we even start releasing tickets, we have to <strong>reserve some of the tickets for speakers</strong> (both those selected and those rejected), <strong>volunteers and sponsors</strong>. And we did reserve a fair amount for all of them.</p>\n<p>Luckily for us, quite a lot of sponsors, volunteers and sponsors already purchased their tickets the regular way, showing their love and support for the European community and WordCamp Europe. <strong>Today we are releasing those unclaimed tickets, making sure that everyone who wants to be in Paris – can be.</strong></p>\n<h2>Finishing the speaker announcements</h2>\n<p>We started rolling out <a href="http://2017.europe.wordcamp.org/speakers/">speaker</a> announcements almost a month ago. Speakers were arranged into thematic groups and we published two <a href="https://2017.europe.wordcamp.org/tag/speakers/">announcements</a> per week. For this (final) week we are making an exception and we&#8217;ll be releasing <strong>three speaker announcements by the end of the week</strong>, with the first one published <a href="http://2017.europe.wordcamp.org/2017/05/02/seventh-group-of-wceu-speakers-k-adam-white-alain-schlesser-ivelina-dimova-dwayne-mcdaniel/">earlier today</a>.</p>\n<p>After the final announcement on Friday, <strong>we&#8217;ll publish the full schedule as well</strong>.</p>\n<h2>WordCamp Europe is (about) you</h2>\n<p>WordCamp Europe grows every year and this is possible thanks to people like you, who support us, who share our stories, values and optimism. <strong>Thank you for being here.</strong> Thank you for being with us on a journey that will result in the biggest WordCamp ever.</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/wpfr/~4/rechJ-wJmQQ" height="1" width="1" alt=""/>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:42:"http://rssnamespace.org/feedburner/ext/1.0";a:1:{s:8:"origLink";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:141:"https://2017.europe.wordcamp.org/2017/05/02/a-busy-week-ahead-of-us-today-were-releasing-reserved-tickets-schedule-to-be-published-on-friday/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:5;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:84:"\n		        \n		        \n		        \n		        \n		        \n		        \n		        \n		    ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:4:{s:0:"";a:5:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:117:"Seventh Group of #WCEU speakers – K. Adam White, Alain Schlesser, Ivelina Dimova, Dwayne McDaniel, and Andrew Nacin";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:51:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/wpfr/~3/VQ6CTluJxPg/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:135:"https://2017.europe.wordcamp.org/2017/05/02/seventh-group-of-wceu-speakers-k-adam-white-alain-schlesser-ivelina-dimova-dwayne-mcdaniel/";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Tue, 02 May 2017 08:58:34 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:428:"\n		        We&#8217;re proud to present our next group of technical talks to you. Please, extend our welcome to K. Adam White, Alain Schlesser, Ivelina Dimova, Dwayne McDaniel, and Andrew Nacin. They will cover development topics ranging from REST API to development &#8230; Continue reading Seventh Group of #WCEU speakers – K. Adam White, Alain Schlesser, Ivelina Dimova, Dwayne McDaniel, and Andrew Nacin  &#8594;		        ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:15:"WordCamp Europe";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4933:"<div id="attachment_5168" style="width: 1410px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img class="size-full wp-image-5168" src="http://2017.europe.wordcamp.org/files/2017/05/wceu-speakers-group-7.jpg" alt="" width="1400" height="800" /><p class="wp-caption-text">WordCamp Europe speakers – K. Adam White, Alain Schlesser, Ivelina Dimova, Dwayne McDaniel, and Andrew Nacin</p></div>\n<p>We&#8217;re proud to present our next group of technical talks to you. Please, extend our welcome to K. Adam White, Alain Schlesser, Ivelina Dimova, Dwayne McDaniel, and Andrew Nacin. They will cover development topics ranging from REST API to development best practices and tricks.</p>\n<p><span id="more-4757"></span></p>\n<h2>K. Adam White &#8211; Data Visualisation with the REST API</h2>\n<p>As an engineer at Bocoup, <a href="http://2017.europe.wordcamp.org/speaker/k-adam-white/">K. Adam White</a> writes web applications, contributes to open-source projects, and evangelises the web as an open platform for technology and collaboration. His talk, &#8220;<a href="http://2017.europe.wordcamp.org/session/data-visualization-with-the-rest-api">Data Visualisation with the REST API</a>,&#8221; will explore how the REST API can be combined with visualisation tools like D3.js to gain new insights into your content. He&#8217;ll demonstrate how build a network diagram to visualize how tags and categories area applied to posts, then explain how to use custom post types and register_meta to build a completely custom dashboard within WordPress for any type of data.</p>\n<h2>Alain Schlesser &#8211; Demystifying the WordPress Bootstrap Process</h2>\n<p>The WordPress bootstrap process is only scarcely documented, with only a very select group of developers that truly know the ins and outs and historical reasons behind the individual bootstrapping steps. Want to know more? <a href="http://2017.europe.wordcamp.org/speaker/alain-schlesser/">Alain</a>, a freelance software engineer and WordPress consultant, will be &#8220;<a href="http://2017.europe.wordcamp.org/session/demystifying-the-wordpress-bootstrap-process">Demystifying the WordPress Bootstrap Process</a>&#8221; at WordCamp Europe this summer. In his talk, Alain will present a detailed overview of the exact execution flow that launches your WordPress site on each page request and introduce a feature project that aims to improve the existing bootstrap process.</p>\n<h2>Ivelina Dimova &#8211; Make your own WP-CLI command in 10min</h2>\n<p><a href="http://2017.europe.wordcamp.org/speaker/ivelina-dimova/">Ivelina</a> is a WordPress developer at CrowdFavorite who is focused on back-end development and passionate about version control systems, deployment and server administration tools. Many in the WordPress community benefit from WP-CLI, a management tool that can make your development flow a lot easier. Ever wondered how that tool can be extended to support custom commands? Ivelina will provide a short overview on just that in &#8220;<a href="http://2017.europe.wordcamp.org/session/make-your-own-wp-cli-command-in-10min">Make your own WP-CLI command in 10min</a>.&#8221;</p>\n<h2>Dwayne McDaniel &#8211; We Are All Making This Up: Improv Lessons For Developers</h2>\n<p><a href="http://2017.europe.wordcamp.org/speaker/dwayne-mcdaniel/">Dwayne</a> is a Community and Agency Success Manager at Pantheon, a role in which he has had the privilege of presenting at multiple events. He will discuss the parallels between the open source development world and improv communities in his talk: &#8220;<a href="http://2017.europe.wordcamp.org/session/we-are-all-making-this-up-improv-lessons-for-developers">We Are All Making This Up: Improv Lessons For Developers</a>.&#8221; The talk will offer guidance on how you can directly apply the core principles from the stagecraft of improv to create better code, smoother projects, and happier customers.</p>\n<h2>Andrew Nacin</h2>\n<p>As lead developer of WordPress, <a href="http://2017.europe.wordcamp.org/speaker/andrew-nacin/">Andrew</a> led major releases, mentored contributors, and spearheaded new development. He has strong feelings about the core philosophies of WordPress, among them “decisions, not options” — software should be opinionated in lieu of burdening the user with too many options.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<hr />\n<h2>Get your ticket today</h2>\n<p>If you haven&#8217;t already, don&#8217;t forget to get <a href="http://2017.europe.wordcamp.org/tickets/">your WordCamp Europe ticket</a>. Your WordCamp Europe ticket covers both days of the conference &#8211; June 16 and 17th &#8211; and contributor day on Thursday, June 15th. It grants you <strong>access to all sessions, lunch, coffee breaks, and the after party</strong>. It also includes an exclusive #WCEU 2017 <strong>t-shirt, stickers, and other great swag</strong>.</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/wpfr/~4/VQ6CTluJxPg" height="1" width="1" alt=""/>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:42:"http://rssnamespace.org/feedburner/ext/1.0";a:1:{s:8:"origLink";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:135:"https://2017.europe.wordcamp.org/2017/05/02/seventh-group-of-wceu-speakers-k-adam-white-alain-schlesser-ivelina-dimova-dwayne-mcdaniel/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:6;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:84:"\n		        \n		        \n		        \n		        \n		        \n		        \n		        \n