(2570, 590, 'rw_bloc1', '<p>[:fr]<em>« As a child, I looked through my classroom windows. Those big, tall windows, closed by catches whose metallic sound when we opened or closed them echoed in the window and throughout the class. They offered the child I was then a necessary escape from my boredom. That lost memory came back to me the day Franck Chalendard told me about his school memories. While I was looking out through the window, he used to look at the blackboard. He would gaze at the blackboard the way one looks at a painting. Was it there that his eye was educated, by the “unlearning” of the written rules? The reverse of instruction, in some way... but perhaps also by persistence. For whereas some of us would flee through the window, he would face the blackboard, and perhaps ultimately look beyond the writing, than its reverse. »<br />\n</em><strong>Sandrine Chalendard</strong></p>\n<h2>Contents</h2>\n<p>Hitherto unpublished texts:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>Pursuing the picture</em>, Karim Ghaddab, art critic;</li>\n<li><em>Taking stock of the body</em>, Tristan Trémeau, art critic and historian;</li>\n<li>“<em>They speak about nothing else</em>”, interview with the artist by Anne Favieroursuivre le tableau, Karim Ghaddab</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Archive texts:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>articles published in art periodicals;</li>\n<li>introductions from older publications;</li>\n<li>texts introducing exhibitions.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Numerous reproductions of works made between 1992 and 2015.</p>\n<p>A complete monographic coverage:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>list of exhibitions;</li>\n<li>bibliographical references.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>[:en]</p>\n<p><em>« As a child, I looked through my classroom windows. Those big, tall windows, closed by catches whose metallic sound when we opened or closed them echoed in the window and throughout the class. They offered the child I was then a necessary escape from my boredom. That lost memory came back to me the day Franck Chalendard told me about his school memories. While I was looking out through the window, he used to look at the blackboard. He would gaze at the blackboard the way one looks at a painting. Was it there that his eye was educated, by the “unlearning” of the written rules? The reverse of instruction, in some way... but perhaps also by persistence. For whereas some of us would flee through the window, he would face the blackboard, and perhaps ultimately look beyond the writing, than its reverse. »<br />\n</em><strong>Sandrine Chalendard</strong></p>\n<h2>Contents</h2>\n<p>Hitherto unpublished texts:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>Pursuing the picture</em>, Karim Ghaddab, art critic;</li>\n<li><em>Taking stock of the body</em>, Tristan Trémeau, art critic and historian;</li>\n<li>“<em>They speak about nothing else</em>”, interview with the artist by Anne Favieroursuivre le tableau, Karim Ghaddab</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Archive texts:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>articles published in art periodicals;</li>\n<li>introductions from older publications;</li>\n<li>texts introducing exhibitions.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Numerous reproductions of works made between 1992 and 2015.</p>\n<p>A complete monographic coverage:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>list of exhibitions;</li>\n<li>bibliographical references.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>[:]</p>\n'),
